{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17526192","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17526192"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:21:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:21:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14125"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14125","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14125"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.03,0.19,0.63,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6805"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105806"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6805","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6805"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14125"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88275"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"1"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1415"},{"type":"tags","id":"2170"},{"type":"tags","id":"2250"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"2986"},{"type":"tags","id":"4632"},{"type":"tags","id":"4922"},{"type":"tags","id":"5611"},{"type":"tags","id":"5619"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15296"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35503"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105806","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105806"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man presents to the hospital for an elective laparoscopic appendicectomy. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He is admitted and taken to the operating theatre.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETwenty minutes after induction of general anaesthesia with propofol and maintenance with sevoflurane, the anaesthetist notices the patient\u0027s end-tidal CO2 is rising rapidly. On examination, his pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 110/75 mmHg, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. The surgeon reports difficulty with the laparoscopy due to abdominal wall rigidity. The anaesthetist immediately performs several key interventions and calls for assistance.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most important step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Administer cefazolin","Administer morphine bolus","Start active cooling measures","Administer dantrolene","Administer rocuronium"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario describes a case of malignant hyperthermia, a rare but potentially fatal genetic disorder triggered by certain anaesthetic agents, particularly volatile anaesthetics like sevoflurane and depolarizing muscle relaxants like suxamethonium. The key features presented here include rapidly rising end-tidal CO2, tachycardia, hyperthermia, and muscle rigidity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate next step in management is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eadminister dantrolene\u003C/strong\u003E. Dantrolene is a specific antidote for malignant hyperthermia - it is a postsynaptic muscle relaxant that inhibits calcium release from the skeletal muscle sarcoplasmic reticulum. Early administration of dantrolene is crucial in preventing the progression of malignant hyperthermia and reducing mortality. While the anaesthetist has appropriately discontinued sevoflurane (a known trigger of malignant hyperthermia) and increased ventilation, these steps alone are insufficient to manage this potentially life-threatening condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdminister morphine bolus\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate in this scenario. While a morphine bolus would be indicated if intraoperative pain was suspected (which can present with muscle tensing and tachycardia), this would not explain the fever and rising end-tidal CO2 seen in this patient. The constellation of symptoms in this stem does not fit with a patient experiencing pain but rather points clearly to malignant hyperthermia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministering rocuronium\u003C/strong\u003E, a non-depolarizing muscle relaxant, would not address the underlying problem of malignant hyperthermia. While it might help with muscle rigidity, it does not treat the cause and could mask further symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStarting active cooling measures\u003C/strong\u003E is an important part of managing malignant hyperthermia, but it is not the most critical first step. Cooling should be initiated after dantrolene administration and discontinuation of triggering agents.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministering cefazolin\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary to treat this presentation. The fever and tachycardia are not due to infection but are instead key features of malignant hyperthermia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter administering dantrolene, additional management steps would include discontinuing volatile anaesthetics, hyperventilating with 100% oxygen, initiating active cooling measures, treating electrolyte abnormalities (particularly hyperkalaemia), and monitoring for complications such as acute kidney injury and disseminated intravascular coagulation. The patient should be closely monitored in an intensive care unit following the event.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Malignant hyperthermia is a rare genetic disorder that can be triggered by volatile anaesthetics and suxamethonium, potentially leading to life-threatening complications.","Key signs of malignant hyperthermia include unexplained tachycardia, rising end-tidal CO2, muscle rigidity, and rapid temperature increase during anaesthesia.","Prompt recognition and immediate treatment with dantrolene, along with discontinuation of triggering agents, are critical for managing malignant hyperthermia."],"references":["Schneiderbanger D, Johannsen S, Roewer N, Schuster F. Management of malignant hyperthermia: diagnosis and treatment. Ther Clin Risk Manag. 2014 May 14;10:355-62. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4027921/","Malignant Hyperthermia: Diagnosis and management of acute crisis. In: UpToDate [Online]. 2019. Available at: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/malignant-hyperthermia-diagnosis-and-management-of-acute-crisis"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88275"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14125"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88275","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88275"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-14T09:32:20+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-14T09:32:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6805"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105806"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"1","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude34","name":"Anaesthesia","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Gradua